'''Lorne B. Groom''' ([[May 13]] [[1919]] &ndash; [[July 24]] [[1994]]<ref>[http://www.legionmagazine.com/en/lastpost/details.asp?alpha=G&offset=5400&LastPostData_ID=167251 Last Post, Canadian Legion Magazine]</ref>) was an [[optometrist]] and political figure in [[New Brunswick]], Canada. He represented Charlotte County in the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] from 1952 to 1957 as a [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservative]] member.

He was born in [[Bocabec, New Brunswick|Bocabec]], [[Charlotte County, New Brunswick]], the son of J. M. Groom. During [[World War II]], he served overseas with the [[Canadian Army]], [[Carleton and York Regiment]], rising to the rank of [[lieutenant]]. Groom lost both legs during the war. At home, he served as president of the St. Croix Branch of the [[Canadian Legion]].

In 1946, Lorne Groom married Ruth Lucille Lindsay. They made their home in St. Stephen where he was a practising optometrist.

In the [[Canadian federal election, 1957|June 10, 1957 Canadian federal election]], Groom ran unsuccessfully for a seat in the [[Canadian House of Commons|House of Commons]]. The [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada]] candidate in the riding of [[New Brunswick Southwest]], he lost to incumbent [[A. Wesley Stuart|Wesley Stuart]].

Lorne Groom died in 1994 and is buried in the [[St. Stephen Rural Cemetery]]. 


